# Bridge Pattern

## Never bypass the bridge
Components call `callTool(rustCommand, input)` from `src/bridge/index.ts` ONLY.
Never import `@tauri-apps/api` or the WASM module directly in any component or utility.

## Bridge config lives in the registry
Non-standard WASM export names → set `wasmExport` on the registry entry.
Non-standard Tauri payload key → set `desktopPayloadKey` on the registry entry.
Do NOT add string special-cases to `bridge/index.ts` or `bridge/desktop.ts`.

---

# History Recording

## Auto-run tools (fire on every keystroke)
Tools that run automatically as the user types MUST use the dual debounce pattern:
- 150ms debounce → call `callTool(cmd, input, { skipHistory: true })` (fast, no history)
- 1500ms debounce → call `callTool(cmd, input)` (captures history entry)

This prevents flooding the history store with every keystroke.
Reference implementation: `src/tools/base64/`

## History is capped
`useHistoryStore` caps at 100 entries per tool (`MAX_HISTORY_PER_TOOL`).
Do not implement your own history trimming in tool components.

---

# Sensitive Tools

## Mark secrets-handling tools with sensitive: true
Any tool that processes secrets, credentials, or private keys must have `sensitive: true`
in its registry entry:
```ts
{ id: "jwt", ..., sensitive: true }
```
The bridge automatically applies `skipHistory: true` for sensitive tools — their
input/output is never recorded in history regardless of how `callTool` is called.

Sensitive tools: jwt, api-key-generator, and any future tool
handling passwords, tokens, private keys, or PII.

The **JWT** tool’s registry `rustCommand` is `tool_jwt_decode`; the Build pane also calls
`tool_jwt_build`. Both panes pass `{ skipHistory: true }` so neither command is recorded
when the combined entry’s `sensitive` flag would not resolve `tool_jwt_build` by name.

